{"ts": "2026-06-08T01:26:00.950843+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have a complete picture of the repository and the issue. Let me analyze the situation.\n\n## Analysis of Issue #3: \"Update baseline policy thresholds\"\n\n**Current state of the files:**\n\n**`policy/zap_policy.yml`** (SHA: `28870c502f...`):\n```yaml\nthresholds:\n  high: fail\n  medium: warn\n  low: pass\n```\n\n**`docs/policy.md`** (SHA: `7d71dfa485...`):\n```markdown\n# ZAP Policy\n\nThe local demo policy treats high-risk alerts as failures, medium-risk alerts as warnings, and low-risk alerts as pass-level findings.\n```\n\n**What the issue requests:**\n> \"Adjust the local policy file so the baseline scan treats medium-risk findings as warnings for this demo app.\"\n\n**Finding:** Both files already satisfy the acceptance criteria:\n\n1. ✅ `policy/zap_policy.yml` already has `medium: warn` — medium-risk findings are treated as warnings.\n2. ✅ `docs/policy.md` already documents: \"medium-risk alerts as warnings.\"\n3. ✅ The `validate_repo.py` script (run via `make validate`) only checks for required file existence and a safety string in `run_zap_baseline.sh` — it does not inspect the policy YAML or docs, so validation is unaffected.\n4. ✅ The change is focused on the documented maintenance request area.\n\n**The requested changes are already implemented in the project files.** No modifications are needed — the policy threshold for medium-risk findings is already set to `warn`, and the documentation accurately reflects this. The existing validation commands (`make validate`) will continue to pass since they don't depend on the policy file contents.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 3987, "prompt_tokens": 10334, "total_tokens": 14321, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 3620, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "i